JavaScript Data Types

JavaScript has 8 data types.

1) Primitive Data Types
// Number
let num = 10;
console.log(typeof num); // number

// String
let name = "John";
console.log(typeof name); // string

// Boolean
let isActive = true;
console.log(typeof isActive); // boolean

// Undefined
let x;
console.log(typeof x); // undefined

// Null
let y = null;
console.log(typeof y); // object (known JS bug)

// BigInt
let big = 12345678901234567890n;
console.log(typeof big); // bigint

// Symbol
let sym = Symbol("id");
console.log(typeof sym); // symbol

Primitive types:

Stored by value

Immutable

2) Non-Primitive Data Type
// Object
let obj = {
    name: "John",
    age: 22
};
console.log(typeof obj); // object

// Array (special type of object)
let arr = [1, 2, 3];
console.log(typeof arr); // object

// Function (also object)
function test() {}
console.log(typeof test); // function

Non-primitive:

Stored by reference

Mutable

5) Type System in JavaScript

JavaScript is:

1) Dynamically Typed
let value = 10;
console.log(typeof value); // number

value = "Hello";
console.log(typeof value); // string

You can change the type of a variable at runtime.

2) Weakly Typed (Type Coercion Happens)
console.log("5" + 2);  // "52" (number converted to string)
console.log("5" - 2);  // 3 (string converted to number)
console.log(true + 1); // 2 (true becomes 1)

JavaScript automatically converts types in some operations.
